<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="../../w/index-title=Calculus_of_variations&action=edit&section=21.php.html" title="Edit section: Notes">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span></h2>
<div class="reflist" style="list-style-type: decimal;">
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-5"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The neighborhood of <span class="texhtml"><i>f</i><sub>0</sub></span> is the part of the given function space where <span class="texhtml">| <i>f</i> - <i>f</i><sub>0</sub>| &lt; h</span> over the whole domain of the functions, with <span class="texhtml">h</span> a positive number that specifies the size of the neighborhood.<sup id="cite_ref-CourHilb1953P169_4-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CourHilb1953P169-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-10"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-10">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The following derivation of the Euler-Lagrange equation corresponds to the derivation on pp. 184–5 of:<br />
<span class="citation book"><a href="Richard_Courant" title="Richard Courant">Courant R</a>, <a href="David_Hilbert" title="David Hilbert">Hilbert D</a> (1953). <i>Methods of Mathematical Physics</i>. <b>Vol. I</b> (First English ed.). New York, New York: Interscience Publishers, Inc. <a href="International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="Special_BookSources/978-0471504474" title="Special:BookSources/978-0471504474">978-0471504474</a>.</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-12"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The product <span class="texhtml"><i>ε</i>Φ′(0)</span> is called the first variation of the functional <span class="texhtml"><i>A</i></span> and is denoted by <span class="texhtml"><i>δA</i></span>. Some references define the <a href="First_variation" title="First variation">first variation</a> differently by leaving out the <span class="texhtml"><i>ε</i></span> factor.</span></li>
</ol>
</div>
